content:
To format a hypothesis in the form of a statement and a question using LaTeX, you can utilize the `\text{}` command within a mathematical formula to include text in a mathematical expression. Here’s how you can structure your hypothesis using the given mathematical formula:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\[
\frac{\text{If } A \text{ is true, is } B \text{ also true?}}{\text{Hypothesis: } A \implies B}
\]

\end{document}
```

In this example:

- The `\documentclass{article}` line specifies the document class.
- The `\usepackage{amsmath}` line includes the AMS math package, which provides additional formatting features for mathematical expressions.
- The `\text{}` command is used to insert non-italicized text within the mathematical environment.
- The `\frac{}` command formats the statement and question as a fraction, with the question as the numerator and the hypothesis as the denominator.

This code will produce a formatted hypothesis statement in LaTeX, blending both text and mathematical elements seamlessly.
